04041nam a2200625Ia 9781501732089DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017320897 a10.7591/97815017320892doi  a(DE-B1597)515154  a(OCoLC)1083627781  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a341.242/22221 aParsons, Craig, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Certain Idea of Europe /cCraig Parsons. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION: The Institutional Construction of Interests -- tPART I: Choosing the Community Model -- tONE. The Parting of the Ways -- tTWO. The Battle Widens -- tTHREE. The Choice for the Community -- tFOUR. Accepting the Community Model -- tPART II: From Community to Union -- tFIVE. Making the Community Monetary -- tSIX. Relaunching the Community -- tSEVEN. Entering Euroland -- tCONCLUSION: Ideas into Interests -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe quasi-federal European Union stands out as the major exception in the thinly institutionalized world of international politics. Something has led Europeans—and only Europeans—beyond the nation-state to a fundamentally new political architecture. Craig Parsons argues in A Certain Idea of Europe that this "something" was a particular set of ideas generated in Western Europe after the Second World War. In Parsons's view, today's European Union reflects the ideological (and perhaps visionary) project of an elite minority. His book traces the progressive victory of this project in France, where the battle over European institutions erupted most divisively. Drawing on archival research and extensive interviews with French policymakers, the author carefully traces a fifty-year conflict between radically different European plans. Only through aggressive leadership did the advocates of a supranational "community" Europe succeed at building the EU and binding their opponents within it. Parsons puts the causal impact of ideas, and their binding effects through institutions, at the center of his book. In so doing he presents a strong logic of "social construction"—a sharp departure from other accounts of EU history that downplay the role of ideas and ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173208940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501732089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501732089/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles